"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93356","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-10-20","<p /> <p>I refer the hon. Member to a previous answer of 4 September 2014 to question 207330, <em>Official Report, </em>column 316W.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201415/cmhansrd/cm140904/text/140904w0001.htm#14090443000651" target="_blank">http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201415/cmhansrd/cm140904/text/140904w0001.htm#14090443000651</a></p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2014-10-20T08:57:01.92526Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93356/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93356/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93356/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-10-14","National Offender Management Service","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how much NOMS has spent on subsidising its retail canteen service contract in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Mr Ben Bradshaw","Exeter","Mr Ben Bradshaw","210431"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93357","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-10-17","<p>The National Offender Management Service's central accounting system has a single accounting code for Public Sector prisoners' earnings. It does not separately identify unemployment pay or details of the number of prisoners in receipt of such payments.</p><p>To obtain this information for both public and private prisons would require us to examine individual prisoner employment records from each establishment to establish those who are in receipt of unemployment pay last week, month and year and this would be a significant exercise and could only be done at disproportionate cost.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","210451","2014-10-17T13:49:27.1452362Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93357/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93357/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93357/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-10-14","Prisoners: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many offenders in each prison in England and Wales were eligible for unemployment pay under paragraph 2.2.1 of Prison Service Order 4460 in the latest (a) week, (b) month and (c) year for which data is available.","false","Biography information for Mr Ben Bradshaw","Exeter","Mr Ben Bradshaw","210452"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93358","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-10-22","<p /> <p>I refer the Honourable Member to my response of 21 October to his earlier question (207329) on this subject: <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=AllQuestions&amp;house=commons%2clords&amp;member=230&amp;dept=54&amp;uin=207329" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=AllQuestions&amp;house=commons%2clords&amp;member=230&amp;dept=54&amp;uin=207329</a></p><p> </p><p>I am sorry for the delay in replying.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2014-10-22T16:55:58.3342808Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93358/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93358/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93358/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-10-14","Prisons: Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many and what proportion of prisoners were working in industrial activity in each public sector prison in England and Wales in each year since 2010-11.","false","Biography information for Mr Ben Bradshaw","Exeter","Mr Ben Bradshaw","210453"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93359","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-10-20","<p /> <p>I refer the hon Member to the reply I gave, the Member for Exeter on 4 September 2014, Official report, column 319W.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2014-10-20T08:26:12.9014404Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93359/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93359/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93359/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-10-14","Open Prisons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many prisoners with determinate sentences with more than two years to serve until their earliest release date were moved to open prisons in (a) 2013-14, (b) 2012-13 and (c) 2011-12.","false","Biography information for Mr Ben Bradshaw","Exeter","Mr Ben Bradshaw","210430"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93360","Ministry of Justice","false","2014-10-21","<p /> <p>The Judicial Complement for magistrates' courts is considered annually, with appropriate consultation with bench chairmen, Lord Chancellor's Advisory Committees and the Chief Magistrate. Workload changes and bench retirements are taken into account, and the aim is to ensure that justices sit a minimum of 13 days per annum, with the average across England and Wales being between 17 and 23 days. Currently the average sittings for Gwent magistrates is about 15 days</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2014-10-21T16:10:42.5126346Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93360/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93360/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93360/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2014-10-14","Magistrates: Gwent","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that there are sufficient magistrates in the Gwent Police Authority area.","false","Biography information for David T. C. Davies","Monmouth","David T. C. Davies","210386"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93362","Department for Transport","false","2014-10-21","<p>The Department is responsible for the policy and legal framework under which penalty fares operate in England and Wales. Train operators that have opted to have a penalty fares scheme must operate it in accordance with Department rules. The rules are designed to be fair, appropriate and consistent.</p><p> </p><p>The penalty fares system is designed to be run by the industry and the Department relies on Passenger Focus (a statutory independent watchdog for rail passengers) to oversee arrangements, as they are best placed to do so.</p><p> </p><p>The Department has regular dialogue with Passenger Focus about a range of issues, including the administration of penalty fares, to inform its view on the effectiveness of the current arrangements.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2014-10-21T11:19:27.4629876Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93362/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93362/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93362/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-10-14","Railways: Penalty Fares","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department is taking to monitor the fairness with which rail companies issue penalty fares notices.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","210355"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93363","Department for Transport","false","2014-10-21","<p>Utility companies have statutory powers to carry out works to maintain or install their apparatus in the street to provide the services that we all rely on. Under the New Roads and Street Works Act 1991, the street authority has a duty to co-ordinate all works on its road network in order to minimise inconvenience to road users, and utilities have a duty to co-operate with them in doing that. The Traffic Management Act 2004 also places a 'Network Management Duty' on authorities to keep traffic moving as far as practical.</p><p> </p><p>In 2012 the Government increased the penalties that local authorities can impose where street works by utility companies overrun their agreed duration, up to a maximum charge of £10,000 a day.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2014-10-21T11:23:10.1251148Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93363/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93363/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93363/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-10-14","Road Works","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will take steps to make utility companies more accountable for traffic delays arising from their street works.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","210399"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93364","Department for Transport","false","2014-10-21","<p>No ministerial visits were made to Torbay constituency in the specified period. As is the convention, however, Members of Parliament would be notified in advance of any Ministerial visits to their constituency if they were to occur.</p><p> </p><p />","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2014-10-21T11:21:45.7108995Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93364/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93364/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93364/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-10-14","Torbay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many visits were made by Ministers of his Department to Torbay constituency in the 12 months to 14 October 2014; whom the invitation for each such visit was issued by; and what the cost to the public purse was of each such visit.","false","Biography information for Mr Adrian Sanders","Torbay","Mr Adrian Sanders","210484"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93365","Department for Transport","false","2014-10-21","<p>Policing in Northern Ireland is devolved; road safety is a matter for the Department of the Environment in Northern Ireland working with Police Service NI and other road safety partners. My officials work closely with their Northern Irish counterparts.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2014-10-21T11:17:53.6687175Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93365/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93365/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93365/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-10-14","Roads: Accidents","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what support the Government is providing to the Police Service of Northern Ireland to reduce the number of deaths on Northern Ireland's roads.","false","Biography information for Ian Paisley","North Antrim","Ian Paisley","210609"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93366","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-10-21","<p /> <p>Income Support provides extra money to help people on a low income. There are no plans to commission a survey to estimate the proportion of claimants who are aware of social tariffs available to help them access landlines.</p>","Wirral West","Esther McVey",,"2014-10-21T14:29:17.3737406Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93366/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93366/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93366/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-14","Income Support","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will commission survey research to make an estimate of the proportion of income support claimants who are aware of social tariffs available to help them access landlines.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Mr Frank Field","210290"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93367","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-10-17","<p /> <p /> <p>Please see the table below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>Operational Operating Costs</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Unit Cost</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total DWP</strong></p><p><strong>Operating Costs</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Unit Cost - Total Costs</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>ESA</strong><strong> Claims</strong></p></td><td><p>£21,639,678.74</p></td><td><p>£25.09</p></td><td><p>£59,680,390.98</p></td><td><p>£66.66</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>ESA</strong><strong> Changes (Incl WCA)</strong></p></td><td><p>£61,465,559.37</p></td><td><p>£12.74</p></td><td><p>£143,414,434.36</p></td><td><p>£28.52</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong> </strong></p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong> </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number of Customers</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>ESA</strong><strong> Changes Processed</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Average Number of Changes</strong></p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>ESA</strong><strong> Changes</strong></p></td><td><p>1,880,822</p></td><td><p>5,028,874</p></td><td><p>2.67</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>The cost of initiating payment of Employment and Support Allowance (ESA) at the assessment rate is provided in ESA Claims. We have provided the annual costs for 13/14 and the Unit Costs. The Unit Cost is the average cost of one ESA Claim through the process.</p><p> </p><p>We have provided the annual cost for ESA changes 13/14 and the unit costs. The Unit Cost is the average cost of one ESA change being made.</p><p> </p><p>We have calculated the average number of changes required by ESA claimants in 13/14 by dividing the number of ESA changes processed by the number of ESA customers.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper",,"2014-10-17T12:59:08.3736682Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93367/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93367/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93367/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-14","Employment and Support Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 21 July 2014 to Question 205882, what the full cost, including apportioned indirect costs, is of initiating payment of employment and support allowance (ESA) at the assessment rate; what the full cost is of an ESA change; and how many changes ESA claimants require on average per year.","false","Biography information for Sheila Gilmore","Edinburgh East","Sheila Gilmore","210313"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93368","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-10-20","<p><strong>Please see table below:</strong></p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td> </td><td><p>Unit Cost - Total Costs</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>JSA Claims (Incl LMDM)</p></td><td><p>£ 27.16</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>(WS) JSA NJI Advice</p></td><td><p>£ 46.48</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The cost of processing a New Claim for Jobseekers’ Allowance is provided in JSA Claims. We have provided the unit costs for 13/14. The Unit Cost is the average cost of one JSA Claim through the process.</p><p> </p><p>For the costs of a jobseekers' allowance interview, we have provided the New Jobseekers’ interview Unit cost for 13/14 under JSA NJI advice. The Unit Cost is the average cost of one New Jobseekers’ interview.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Wirral West","Esther McVey",,"2014-10-20T16:08:07.8133654Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93368/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93368/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93368/answer","Wirral West","Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93368/answer/previousversion/22797","Biography information for Esther McVey","29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-14","Jobseeker's Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 21 July 2014 to Question 205883, what the full cost, including apportioned indirect costs, is of processing a new claim for jobseeker's allowance; and what the full cost is of a jobseeker's allowance interview.","false","Biography information for Sheila Gilmore","Edinburgh East","Sheila Gilmore","210314"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93369","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-10-17","<p>Departmental statisticians are continuing to develop measures around clearance times and waiting times to ensure they provide a rounded and representative picture of PIP system performance, improvement activity and the claimants’ experience. These statistics will be published once/when they are ready, with the release pre-announced in line with United Kingdom Statistics Authority release protocols.</p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper","210327","2014-10-17T11:29:05.3949614Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93369/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93369/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93369/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-14","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many applications for personal independence payments have taken longer than 26 weeks to receive a decision.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","210331"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93370","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-10-17","<p /> <p>We keep the time taken to process claims under constant review and we are absolutely committed to improving performance. We are already seeing improvements to our processes and outcomes and will continue to work further to reduce processing times and levels of work outstanding.</p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper",,"2014-10-17T11:29:50.208958Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93370/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93370/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93370/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-14","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps he has taken to ensure that personal independence payments applications are not delayed to the extent that supporting medical information becomes outdated.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","210332"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93371","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-10-17","<p /> <p>Departmental statisticians are continuing to develop measures around clearance times and waiting times to ensure they provide a rounded and representative picture of PIP system performance, improvement activity and the claimants’ experience. These statistics will be published once/when they are ready, with the release pre-announced in line with United Kingdom Statistics Authority release protocols.</p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper","210331","2014-10-17T11:29:05.0043227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93371/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93371/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93371/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-14","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, when he plans to publish data on the average wait for an assessment for a personal independence payment.","false","Biography information for Michael Dugher","Barnsley East","Michael Dugher","210327"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93372","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-10-17","<p>The latest available data for personal independence payment claims, including details on the number of people who have applied for the benefit and the number of claims that have been cleared, have been published and are available from the GOV.UK website: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/personal-independence-payment-april-2013-to-july-2014" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/personal-independence-payment-april-2013-to-july-2014</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper",,"2014-10-17T11:00:35.9498093Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93372/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93372/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93372/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-14","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people who have applied for personal independence payments are waiting to receive a decision.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","210334"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93373","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-10-17","<p /> <p>It is possible to qualify for ESA through the application of Regulations 29(2)(b) and 35(2)(b) where insufficient points have been allocated in a Work Capability Assessment. It is thus not possible to answer the first part of this question.</p><p> </p><p>The information requested in the second part is not readily available and to provide it would incur disproportionate cost.</p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper",,"2014-10-17T10:40:27.5875346Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93373/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93373/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93373/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-14","Employment and Support Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people stopped claiming employment and support allowance (ESA) in 2013 after gaining insufficient points in a Work Capability Assessment; and how many such people were claiming jobseeker's allowance within four weeks of their ESA claim ending.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","210472"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93374","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-10-21","<p>The latest available data for personal independence payment claims, including details on the number of people receiving the mobility component, have been published and are available from the GOV.UK website:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/personal-independence-payment-april-2013-to-july-2014" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/personal-independence-payment-april-2013-to-july-2014</a></p><p> </p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper",,"2014-10-21T13:38:04.8990523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93374/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93374/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93374/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-14","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people are entitled to the mobility element of personal independence payments.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","210518"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93375","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-10-17","<p>Motability is an independent registered charity. The Department works closely with Motability and facilitates the transfer of benefit to Motability on behalf of those claimants who have chosen to join the Motability schemes.</p><p>Responsibility for the charity’s policies and operational strategy falls to the Governors and Director of Motability. Motability is wholly responsible for the administration of the Motability scheme including collating its own management information. Questions about the number of cars and scooters allocated by Motability can be sent to: Declan O'Mahony, Director, Motability, Warwick House, Roydon Road, Harlow, Essex CM19 5PX.</p><p>Information about complaints received about Motability is not available and can only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper","210520 ; 210550","2014-10-17T10:39:24.124095Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93375/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93375/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93375/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-14","Personal Independence Payment: Motability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many scooters have been allocated under the mobility element of personal independence payments in the last year.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","210519"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93376","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-10-17","<p>Motability is an independent registered charity. The Department works closely with Motability and facilitates the transfer of benefit to Motability on behalf of those claimants who have chosen to join the Motability schemes.</p><p>Responsibility for the charity’s policies and operational strategy falls to the Governors and Director of Motability. Motability is wholly responsible for the administration of the Motability scheme including collating its own management information. Questions about the number of cars and scooters allocated by Motability can be sent to: Declan O'Mahony, Director, Motability, Warwick House, Roydon Road, Harlow, Essex CM19 5PX.</p><p>Information about complaints received about Motability is not available and can only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper","210519 ; 210550","2014-10-17T10:39:24.2022038Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93376/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93376/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93376/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-14","Personal Independence Payment: Motability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many cars have been allocated under the mobility element of personal independence payments in the last year.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","210520"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93377","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-10-20","<p>The Department for Work and Pensions publishes monitoring returns from local authorities that give a breakdown of Discretionary Housing Payment (DHP) awards by broad category, including to recipients of Housing Benefit subject to Local Housing Allowance calculations. Further detail, for example awards to those subject to the Shared Accommodation Rate (SAR), is not available. Returns are voluntary and information is not provided by all local authorities. The returns give the number of awards, which may not equate to the number of people receiving them; some people may receive more than one award over the period.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The latest publication is available at the following weblink:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/use-of-discretionary-housing-payments-2013-to-2014" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/use-of-discretionary-housing-payments-2013-to-2014</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Department’s housing benefit administrative database, compiled from electronic data supplied by local authorities, identifies by gender and age those Housing Benefit claimants that are assessed by the SAR in the given area. These data are taken from scans of local authority systems. They also hold some information on whether a DHP is being made to the claimant at that time. The recording of this information on the electronic data is incomplete and not reliable.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Thornbury and Yate","Steve Webb",,"2014-10-20T15:18:33.0793751Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93377/answer","Biography information for Steve Webb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93377/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93377/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-14","Housing Benefit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 13 October 2014 to Question 209233 for what reason the information is not available.","false","Biography information for Mr David Anderson","Blaydon","Mr David Anderson","210521"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93378","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-10-17","<p /> <p>The department uses a range of metrics to track and manage timeliness of payments within the benefits system.</p><p> </p><p>Our transparency indicators also include an overall productivity measure.</p>","Wirral West","Esther McVey",,"2014-10-17T13:47:58.0112332Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93378/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93378/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93378/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-14","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what measures he uses to assess the timeliness of payments in the benefits system.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","210464"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93379","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-10-20","<p /> <p>The Secretary of State for Work and Pensions and the ministers of his Department have made no visits in the 12 months to October 2014 to the Torbay constituency in a ministerial capacity. <strong> </strong></p>","Thornbury and Yate","Steve Webb",,"2014-10-20T14:01:59.6871866Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93379/answer","Biography information for Steve Webb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93379/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93379/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-14","Torbay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many visits were made by Ministers of his Department to Torbay constituency in the 12 months to 14 October 2014; whom the invitation for each such visit was issued by; and what the cost to the public purse was of each such visit.","false","Biography information for Mr Adrian Sanders","Torbay","Mr Adrian Sanders","210486"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93380","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-10-21","<p>For most recent changes please see the following link for the Government response to Matthew Oakley’s Review of Sanctions:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/jobseekers-allowance-sanctions-independent-review-government-response" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/jobseekers-allowance-sanctions-independent-review-government-response</a></p><p> </p>","Wirral West","Esther McVey",,"2014-10-21T14:48:52.0559099Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93380/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93380/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93380/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-14","Social Security Benefits: Disqualification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what changes have been made to the benefits sanctions regime since 2010.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","210487"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93381","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-10-17","<p>The information you have requested is not available. The Department published its strategy for releasing official statistics on Universal Credit in September 2013 which can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/universal-credit-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/universal-credit-statistics</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Wirral West","Esther McVey",,"2014-10-17T13:49:34.3380902Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93381/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93381/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93381/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-14","Universal Credit: Warrington","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many universal credit claimants in Warrington have been sanctioned for failure to attend a mandatory work placement after they have reported a change of circumstances but before they are advised of their entitlement to another benefit.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","210534"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93382","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-10-21","<p /> <p>The information is in the table:</p><p><strong> </strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Jobseekers Allowance for 18-21 year-olds in Scotland</p></td><td><p><strong>2011/12</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012/13</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013/14</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Claimants (thousands)</p></td><td><p>25,900</p></td><td><p>23,400</p></td><td><p>18,100</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Expenditure (nominal, £m)</p></td><td><p>£74</p></td><td><p>£69</p></td><td><p>£52</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Average payment per week</p></td><td><p>£54.43</p></td><td><p>£57.23</p></td><td><p>£57.39</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><strong>Notes: </strong></p><p> </p><p>1. Estimates are based on the Work and Pensions Longitudinal Study, Quarterly Statistical Enquiry and expenditure data for Jobseeker’s Allowance.</p><p>2. Caseload and average amounts paid are averaged over each financial year.</p>","Wirral West","Esther McVey",,"2014-10-21T15:15:15.786401Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93382/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93382/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93382/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-14","Jobseeker's Allowance: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people aged 18 to 21 claimed jobseekers allowance in Scotland; what total amount was claimed in each of the last three years; and what the average amount claimed per person was in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Dr Eilidh Whiteford","Banff and Buchan","Dr Eilidh Whiteford","210490"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93383","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-10-21","<p /> <p>In Universal Credit a claimant is gainfully self-employed where:</p><p>· They are carrying on a trade, profession or vocation as their main form of employment;</p><p>· Their earnings from the trade, profession or vocation are self-employed earnings;</p><p>· The trade, profession or vocation is organised, developed, regular and carried on in expectation of profit.</p><p> </p><p>The freelance status of performers would not affect their eligibility for Universal Credit, or whether they meet the definition of gainful self-employment .</p><p> </p><p>Whilst the self-employment must be regular, neither the work patterns nor the claimant’s earnings need to be so. The Department recognises that self-employment work patterns often vary and a range of factors can influence the amount and duration of self-employed work.</p><p> </p><p>Universal Credit is assessed and paid monthly, which enables it to adjust quickly to take account of changes in earnings, ensuring claimants receive the right level of support at the right time.</p><p> </p>","Wirral West","Esther McVey",,"2014-10-21T16:58:57.4331431Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93383/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93383/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93383/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-14","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will take steps to ensure that the gainful self-employment test under universal credit takes into account (a) the freelance status of performers and (b) the irregular work patterns of performers when applied to those applicants.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","210489"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93384","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-10-17","<p>The information you have requested is currently not available. The Department published its strategy for releasing official statistics on Universal Credit in September 2013 which can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/universal-credit-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/universal-credit-statistics</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Wirral West","Esther McVey",,"2014-10-17T13:52:28.2810411Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93384/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93384/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93384/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-14","Universal Credit: Warrington","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the average time taken by Warrington Jobcentre Plus is to review the conditionality group of a universal credit claimant who reports a change of circumstances.","false","Biography information for Helen Jones","Warrington North","Helen Jones","210535"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93385","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-10-21","<p /> <p>No recent discussions have taken place between the Department and disability groups on this specific issue.</p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper",,"2014-10-21T11:11:32.7410231Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93385/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93385/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93385/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-14","Employment and Support Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what discussions he has had with disability groups on replacing tax-free disability living allowance and incapacity benefit with taxable contribution-based employment and support allowance.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","210385"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93386","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-10-20","<p>For cases administered by the Child Support Agency, the number of Children Benefiting from maintenance has decreased from 871,800 in March 2014 to 846,300 in June 2014. This information is routinely published in the CSA Quarterly Summary of Statistics available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/child-support-agency-quarterly-summary-statistics--2" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/child-support-agency-quarterly-summary-statistics--2</a></p><p> </p><p>The change in trend can be attributed to the fact that since 25 November 2013 all new applications are now being processed by the Child Maintenance Service. We are not yet in a position to release full statistics for these cases and are therefore unable to provide the information requested. When system data becomes available and fully assured they will be released as part of a managed process, which will be pre-announced and in line with the Code of Practice for Official Statistics.</p><p> </p><p>The figures above relate to those receiving support within the statutory child maintenance schemes. Children also benefit from financial support as part of arrangements made outside the statutory schemes, including private arrangements made between the separated parents, which are known as &quot;family-based arrangements”. Our planned approach to measuring this will be considered as part of an evaluation strategy, which we will publish by the end of 2014.</p><p> </p>","Thornbury and Yate","Steve Webb",,"2014-10-20T15:07:34.874016Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93386/answer","Biography information for Steve Webb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93386/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93386/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-14","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what change there has been in the proportion of children living in separated families who receive regular financial support from the non-resident parent since May 2014.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","210433"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93387","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-10-21","<p /> <p>The number of unemployed people is measured by the Labour Force Survey (LFS). The LFS is not able to identify these groups separately. Statistics on registrations are no longer collected as unemployed people are not required to register at a Jobcentre.</p>","Wirral West","Esther McVey",,"2014-10-21T15:07:54.9642226Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93387/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93387/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93387/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-14","Unemployment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many unemployed people are (a) not in receipt of any of the benefits to which they are entitled and (b) not registered at job centres.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","210444"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93388","Cabinet Office","false","2014-10-20","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p><p> </p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson",,"2014-10-20T15:42:09.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93388/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93388/answer","PQ 210338 ONS 351.pdf","PQ 210338 ONS 351.pdf","ONS Letter to Member - EU Migrants","ONS Letter to Member - EU Migrants","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93388/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2014-10-14","Immigration: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will make an estimate of the number of EU migrants arriving in the UK for work since 1 January 2014.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","210338"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93389","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-10-21","<p>The budget for the Disability Confident campaign events has come from the Disability Directorate non-staff allocation; and from contributions in kind from Disability Confident partners.</p><p> </p><p>In the Financial Year 2013-2014, £100,000 was allocated to the Disability Confident campaign events; and an estimated further £215,000 was contributed in kind by external partners.</p><p> </p><p>In the current Financial Year, around £20,000 has been spent so far on the campaign.</p><p> </p><p>The effect of this spending has to date been measured in terms of the number of employers reached directly through the events (1,100) and the reach and impact of communications via no-cost channels such as social media. For example on 18 July, the 1<sup>st</sup> anniversary of the launch of the campaign, we achieved a significant reach on Twitter (a total of 19m impressions), delivering wider awareness of the campaign and prompting partners and stakeholders to voice their support and commitment. Over the second year of the campaign, we will continue to build on the reach of communications, but will also assess specific, measurable, action taken by employers as a result of the campaign.</p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper",,"2014-10-21T11:36:27.0500768Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93389/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93389/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93389/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-14","Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how much his Department is spending in the Disability Confident campaign; and how the effect of such spending is being measured.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","210432"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93390","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-10-20","<p>The Government regularly produces analysis of the cumulative impact of all coalition changes, including welfare, on households across the income distribution. In the interests of transparency this Government introduced the publication of such documents (produced by HM Treasury), alongside every Budget and Autumn Statement. The most recent update was published with the Budget in March 2014, and can be found using the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/293738/budget_2014_distributional_analysis.pdf" target="_blank">Impact on households: distributional analysis to accompany Budget 2014</a></p><p> </p><p>This analysis estimates the effect of coalition measures from all fiscal events from the Budget in June 2010 to the Budget in March 2014. It also includes changes that were announced before the Budget in June 2010 that have been implemented by this Government.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Wirral West","Esther McVey",,"2014-10-20T15:53:10.181172Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93390/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93390/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93390/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-14","Welfare State: Reform","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if his Department will assess the cumulative effect of welfare policy reforms instituted since May 2010; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Fabian Hamilton","Leeds North East","Fabian Hamilton","210415"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93391","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-10-21","<p /> <p>DWP does not issue any guidance to local authorities around ensuring that benefit claimants are not given conflicting appointments.</p><p> </p><p>However, whenever a benefit claimant is required to attend an interview with a DWP adviser they are given information, verbally and/or in writing, which includes details about the interview itself and what they are required to do if they are unable to attend that interview.</p>","Wirral West","Esther McVey",,"2014-10-21T13:26:18.3283088Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93391/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93391/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93391/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-14","Social Security Benefits: Disqualification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what guidance his Department gives to local authorities on ensuring that benefit claimants are not given conflicting appointments which carry non-attendance sanctions by both his Department and those authorities.","false","Biography information for Fabian Hamilton","Leeds North East","Fabian Hamilton","210416"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93392","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-10-21","<p /> <p>Information about claimants who were entitled to means tested ESA within a month of their entitlement to contributory ESA expiring are in the table below.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Number of Claimants claiming means tested ESA within a month of contributory ESA expiring</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/13</p></td><td><p>69,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>59,000</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Information on claimants qualifying for Income Support, income-related Jobseeker’s Allowance, Pension Credit and claimants who have moved into work as a result of time limiting is not collated centrally and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>Notes:</p><p> </p><p>1. The 2012/13 data includes a number of cases who had been in receipt of contributory ESA for 12 months or more at the point the change was introduced.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>2. This estimate is based on the Generalised Matching Service, which is a departmental data capture tool. The data have not been fully quality-assured. This type of information does not form part of the regular official statistics outputs that are released by the Department in accordance with the UK Statistics Authority’s Code of Practice.</p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper",,"2014-10-21T16:37:14.6186685Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93392/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93392/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93392/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-14","Employment and Support Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what proportion of people no longer eligible for contributions-based employment and support allowance (ESA) because of time-limiting to one year have qualified for an alternative income-related benefit at the termination of contributory ESA payments in each year since implementation of that policy; and what estimate his Department has made of the proportion of the people affected by that policy who have moved into work as a result.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","210605"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93393","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-10-20","<p>The Pensions Regulator produces free guidance for trustees via the online Trustee Toolkit. The Trustee Toolkit was updated last week, with new material on the extent to which trustees should take account of social, environmental or ethical considerations when taking investment decisions. This new material reflects the outcomes of the Law Commission’s recent review of fiduciary duties.</p><p> </p>","Thornbury and Yate","Steve Webb",,"2014-10-20T13:41:46.9527017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93393/answer","Biography information for Steve Webb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93393/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93393/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-14","Pension Funds","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what guidance the Government provides to pension fund trustees on the consideration of environmental, social and governance factors as part of their fiduciary duties; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","210528"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93394","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-10-17","<p /> <p>Ministers have regularly met Lord Sterling, the unpaid chairman of Motability. They have also conducted visits to the Motability charity, at which executives were present.</p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper",,"2014-10-17T12:37:29.3745799Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93394/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93394/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93394/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-14","Motability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many times in the last three years Ministers in his Department have met executives from Motability.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","210548"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93395","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-10-17","<p /> <p>The mobility element of Personal Independence Payment is estimated to account for around 36 per cent of total spending on the benefit.</p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper",,"2014-10-17T12:33:22.9638517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93395/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93395/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93395/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-14","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the annual cost to his Department of the mobility element of personal independence payments.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","210549"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93396","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2014-10-17","<p /> <p>Motability is an independent registered charity. The Department works closely with Motability and facilitates the transfer of benefit to Motability on behalf of those claimants who have chosen to join the Motability schemes.</p><p>Responsibility for the charity’s policies and operational strategy falls to the Governors and Director of Motability. Motability is wholly responsible for the administration of the Motability scheme including collating its own management information. Questions about the number of cars and scooters allocated by Motability can be sent to: Declan O'Mahony, Director, Motability, Warwick House, Roydon Road, Harlow, Essex CM19 5PX.</p><p>Information about complaints received about Motability is not available and can only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","Forest of Dean","Mr Mark Harper","210519 ; 210520","2014-10-17T10:39:24.0419584Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93396/answer","Biography information for Mr Mark Harper","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93396/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93396/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2014-10-14","Motability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many complaints about Motability have been raised with his Department in the last three years.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","210550"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93397","Department of Health","false","2014-10-22","<p>The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) published draft highly specialised technologies guidance on eculizumab for the treatment of atypical haemolytic uraemic syndrome on 4 September. Stakeholders had until 25 September to comment on NICE’s draft recommendations and I understand that it currently expects to issue final guidance to the NHS in January 2015.</p><p> </p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2014-10-22T12:05:46.7129266Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93397/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93397/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93397/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-10-14","Haemolytic Uraemic Syndrome","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by the Minister of State for Care and Support, Norman Lamb MP, on 26 June (HC Deb, 278W), what progress has been made by the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence’s evaluation committee in the evaluation of eculizumab to treat atypical haemolytic uraemic syndrome.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL2063"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93398","Department of Health","false","2014-10-22","<p>The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) is currently following an interim methods guide for its highly specialised technologies programme. We understand that NICE expects to commence a review of its methods guide later this year. As part of this review, NICE plans to undertake a public consultation in 2015.</p><p> </p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2014-10-22T12:06:28.4527131Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93398/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93398/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93398/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-10-14","National Institute for Health and Care Excellence","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence will review its programme for evaluating highly specialised technologies.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL2064"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93399","Department of Health","false","2014-10-24","<p>The Secretary of State for Health, in his Annual Assessment of National Health Service England’s Annual Report for the last financial year (2013-14), has stated that “[NHS England] must […] ensure that spending controls are effective, particularly around specialised commissioning.” A copy of the Secretary of State’s Annual Assessment has been placed in the library.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Section 3B(1)(d) of the National Health Service Act 2006, as amended by the Health and Social Care Act 2012, gives the Secretary of State the power to require the NHS Commissioning Board (known as NHS England) to commission prescribed services or facilities in relation to England by making regulations. Using this power, the Secretary of State may require NHS England to commission specialised services for people with rare or very rare conditions. Before deciding whether to make regulations, the Secretary of State must (a) obtain appropriate advice for that purpose and (b) consult NHS England. The Prescribed Specialised Services Advisory Group (PSSAG) is a Department of Health appointed expert committee which was established in 2013 to provide the Secretary of State with this advice. NHS England commissions all the services listed in Schedule 4 of The National Health Service Commissioning Board and Clinical Commissioning Groups (Responsibilities and Standing Rules) Regulations 2012.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The scope of specialised services directly commissioned by NHS England is kept under review.</p><p> </p>",,"Earl Howe","HL2066 ; HL2067","2014-10-24T11:31:33.6695234Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93399/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93399/answer","Annual_Assessment_of_NHSE.pdf","Annual_Assessment_of_NHSE.pdf","Annual Assesment of NHSE","Annual Assesment of NHSE","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93399/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-10-14","Health Services","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is the nature of the relationship between Ministers, the Prescribed Specialised Services Advisory Group and NHS England in prescribing specialised services under the Health and Social Care Act 2012.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL2065"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93400","Department of Health","false","2014-10-24","<p>The Secretary of State for Health, in his Annual Assessment of National Health Service England’s Annual Report for the last financial year (2013-14), has stated that “[NHS England] must […] ensure that spending controls are effective, particularly around specialised commissioning.” A copy of the Secretary of State’s Annual Assessment has been placed in the library.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Section 3B(1)(d) of the National Health Service Act 2006, as amended by the Health and Social Care Act 2012, gives the Secretary of State the power to require the NHS Commissioning Board (known as NHS England) to commission prescribed services or facilities in relation to England by making regulations. Using this power, the Secretary of State may require NHS England to commission specialised services for people with rare or very rare conditions. Before deciding whether to make regulations, the Secretary of State must (a) obtain appropriate advice for that purpose and (b) consult NHS England. The Prescribed Specialised Services Advisory Group (PSSAG) is a Department of Health appointed expert committee which was established in 2013 to provide the Secretary of State with this advice. NHS England commissions all the services listed in Schedule 4 of The National Health Service Commissioning Board and Clinical Commissioning Groups (Responsibilities and Standing Rules) Regulations 2012.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The scope of specialised services directly commissioned by NHS England is kept under review.</p><p> </p>",,"Earl Howe","HL2065 ; HL2067","2014-10-24T11:31:34.6500285Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93400/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93400/answer","Annual_Assessment_of_NHSE.pdf","Annual_Assessment_of_NHSE.pdf","Annual Assesment of NHSE","Annual Assesment of NHSE","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93400/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-10-14","Health Services","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to change the scope of specialised services directly commissioned by NHS England.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL2066"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93401","Department of Health","false","2014-10-24","<p>The Secretary of State for Health, in his Annual Assessment of National Health Service England’s Annual Report for the last financial year (2013-14), has stated that “[NHS England] must […] ensure that spending controls are effective, particularly around specialised commissioning.” A copy of the Secretary of State’s Annual Assessment has been placed in the library.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Section 3B(1)(d) of the National Health Service Act 2006, as amended by the Health and Social Care Act 2012, gives the Secretary of State the power to require the NHS Commissioning Board (known as NHS England) to commission prescribed services or facilities in relation to England by making regulations. Using this power, the Secretary of State may require NHS England to commission specialised services for people with rare or very rare conditions. Before deciding whether to make regulations, the Secretary of State must (a) obtain appropriate advice for that purpose and (b) consult NHS England. The Prescribed Specialised Services Advisory Group (PSSAG) is a Department of Health appointed expert committee which was established in 2013 to provide the Secretary of State with this advice. NHS England commissions all the services listed in Schedule 4 of The National Health Service Commissioning Board and Clinical Commissioning Groups (Responsibilities and Standing Rules) Regulations 2012.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The scope of specialised services directly commissioned by NHS England is kept under review.</p><p> </p>",,"Earl Howe","HL2065 ; HL2066","2014-10-24T11:31:31.9429288Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93401/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93401/answer","Annual_Assessment_of_NHSE.pdf","Annual_Assessment_of_NHSE.pdf","Annual Assesment of NHSE","Annual Assesment of NHSE","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93401/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-10-14","Health Services","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the commissioning of specialised services by NHS England.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL2067"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93402","Department of Health","false","2014-10-28","<p>The Government holds the National Health Service to account for achieving parity of esteem as required by the Health and Social Care Act 2012, through setting objectives in the NHS England Mandate for 2013-15 and the refreshed Mandate for 2014-15. In addition to measuring progress on specific objectives in the Mandate, outcomes for mental health patients are monitored through the NHS Outcomes Framework, which forms an essential part of the way in which the Secretary of State holds NHS England to account.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Our recently published five-year plan,<em> Achieving Better Access to Mental Health Services by 2020,</em> sets out action the Government is taking to provide better access to mental health services within the next year, including the first ever national waiting time standards for mental health services. It also sets out our vision for further progress by 2020.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>£40 million in additional funding has been identified to enable change in the current financial year, and a further £80 million will be freed up for 2015-16 to support implementation of waiting times in mental health services.</p><p> </p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2014-10-28T15:13:50.9745053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93402/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93402/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93402/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2014-10-14","Mental Health Services","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what action they will take to ensure that NHS England ensures parity of esteem as required by the Health and Social Care Act 2012, the NHS Mandate for 2013 to 2015 and the Refreshed Mandate for 2014 to 2015.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL2068"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93403","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-10-22","<p>The provision of support for low-income council taxpayers, as well as decisions on collection and enforcement, are matters for local authorities. It is for them to ensure that the effect of local schemes on specific groups of council taxpayers is proportionate and fair.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>We issued guidance to councils last year to provide more protection for people against aggressive bailiffs and other unreasonable practices. This is available at: https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/council-tax</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","HL2070 ; HL2071","2014-10-22T15:41:31.5481582Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93403/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93403/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93403/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-10-14","Council Tax","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment has been made of the impact of the levying of council tax on low income households, both on local authorities in collecting such charges and on households unable to pay.","false","Biography information for Lord Ouseley",,"Lord Ouseley","HL2069"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93404","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-10-22","<p>The provision of support for low-income council taxpayers, as well as decisions on collection and enforcement, are matters for local authorities. It is for them to ensure that the effect of local schemes on specific groups of council taxpayers is proportionate and fair.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>We issued guidance to councils last year to provide more protection for people against aggressive bailiffs and other unreasonable practices. This is available at: https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/council-tax</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","HL2069 ; HL2071","2014-10-22T15:41:32.1755475Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93404/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93404/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93404/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-10-14","Council Tax","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what estimates have been made of the amount of money local authorities would need to find to retain discounts for those low income households which have failed to date to pay the council tax demanded of them.","false","Biography information for Lord Ouseley",,"Lord Ouseley","HL2070"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93405","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2014-10-22","<p>The provision of support for low-income council taxpayers, as well as decisions on collection and enforcement, are matters for local authorities. It is for them to ensure that the effect of local schemes on specific groups of council taxpayers is proportionate and fair.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>We issued guidance to councils last year to provide more protection for people against aggressive bailiffs and other unreasonable practices. This is available at: https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/council-tax</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","HL2069 ; HL2070","2014-10-22T15:41:32.317985Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93405/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93405/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93405/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2014-10-14","Council Tax","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what consideration has been given to supporting low income households facing debt, repossession or bankruptcy over unpaid council tax following reductions in council tax benefit.","false","Biography information for Lord Ouseley",,"Lord Ouseley","HL2071"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93406","HM Treasury","false","2014-10-27","<p>On 6 August, the Chancellor announced a major programme of work looking into digital currencies and associated technologies, with a particular focus on whether they should be regulated. The Government is now considering the benefits offered by digital currencies and the technology that underpins them, and whether it should take action to support innovation in this area. At the same time, the Government is examining the risks presented by digital currencies, and assessing whether action is required to mitigate any concerns. The Government is engaging with a wide range of stakeholders, including the UK Digital Currency Association, as part of this work.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Deighton",,"2014-10-27T12:43:05.3499054Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93406/answer","Biography information for Lord Deighton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93406/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93406/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-10-14","Currencies","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what work is being undertaken by HM Treasury in respect of bitcoin and other digital currencies in the context of the speech by the Chancellor of the Exchequer on 6 August; and what consultation has taken place with the UK Digital Currency Association, as the representative body of those United Kingdom businesses engaged with digital currency.","false","Biography information for Lord Harris of Haringey",,"Lord Harris of Haringey","HL2072"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93407","Department for Transport","false","2014-10-28","<p>The Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency (DVLA) will continue to issue printed renewal reminders which will be sent to vehicle keepers before the vehicle excise duty is due to expire.</p>",,"Baroness Kramer",,"2014-10-28T15:29:35.1265275Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93407/answer","Biography information for Baroness Kramer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93407/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93407/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-10-14","Motor Vehicles: Excise Duties","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether, following the introduction of paperless processing of vehicle excise duty, the Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency will continue to issue written notices to vehicle owners when their licences are due to expire.","false","Biography information for Lord Trefgarne",,"Lord Trefgarne","HL2073"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93408","Department for International Development","false","2014-10-21","<p>The UK Government is using all the resources at its disposal to push back and ultimately seek to destroy ISIL. This includes providing military assistance to the Kurdish Peshmerga forces fighting ISIL so that they can restore control over the areas taken by ISIL, deploying a specialist team of Army trainers into Erbil, to provide Iraqi forces with training, and the RAF carrying out surveillance flights to provide greater situational awareness. The UK will continue to closely monitor the situation in the Kurdish and wider regions of Iraq.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In addition, DFID has provided £23m of UK Aid to Iraq, £17.5 million of which is funding NGOs, the UN and the Red Cross who continue to provide support to displaced people, including carrying out protection activities. All UK funded aid is distributed on the basis of need to ensure civilians are not discriminated against. Our aid is reaching displaced people across Iraq, including in the Kurdish region, to which many Christians and Yazidis have fled.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Secretary of State for DFID visited Iraq in August and urged the then Designate, now confirmed in post, Iraqi Prime Minister, Haida al-Abadi, to ensure that his government protects all minorities in Iraq, promotes human rights and asserts the rule of law. The UK has also helped to secure a UN Human Rights Council Resolution mandating the UN urgently to investigate and report on ISIL abuses.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Northover",,"2014-10-21T16:34:47.5736019Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93408/answer","Biography information for Baroness Northover","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93408/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93408/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-10-14","Iraq","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the safety of Christian and Yezidi refugees in the Kurdish region in Iraq and the likelihood of an IS-led genocide against them.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL2074"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93409","Home Office","false","2014-10-27","<p>The Government believes that humanitarian aid and actively seeking to end the conflicts in Syria and Iraq are the most effective ways for the UK to help the majority of refugees, rather than increasing resettlement. We have made our position on this clear in relevant discussions with other EU Member States and the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR). We are aware that EU Member States have responded to the crises in different ways; it is right that the international community should consider all available means to relieve the suffering of the Syrian and Iraqi peoples. However, the UK’s overall contribution stands comparison with any in the world.</p><p> </p><p>To date we have committed £700 million to the Syrian relief effort, making us the second largest bilateral donor after the USA, and £23 million in aid to Iraq. UK funding is helping hundred of thousands of refugees; compared with aid, resettlement can only ever support a comparatively small number of people in need. We also support efforts to find a political solution to the Syrian conflict, and we are working with the Iraqi government and the international community to tackle the threat posed by IS and promote an inclusive, sovereign and democratic Iraq which will protect all Iraqi citizens.</p><p> </p><p>To complement our humanitarian aid, we operate the Syrian Vulnerable Persons Relocation scheme to relocate to the UK the most vulnerable displaced Syrians who cannot be supported effectively in the long term in the region. In addition, the Government carefully considers each asylum application lodged in the UK, including those made by Syrian and Iraqi nationals on the grounds of religious persecution, on its individual merits, to ensure we grant protection to those who genuinely need it.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2014-10-27T12:30:23.0429145Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93409/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93409/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93409/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-10-14","Middle East","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what discussions they have had with other European Union member states about scaling up the resettlement programme for refugees displaced by fighting in Syria and Iraq; and what is their policy in regard to applications for asylum from displaced Yezidis and Christians from those countries.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL2075"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93410","Department for International Development","false","2014-10-21","<p>DFID is already delivering at scale in Iraq. UK Aid has provided £17.5 million (of a total £23m) in funding to the UN, NGOs (Non-Government Organisations) and ICRC (International Committee of the Red Cross) for projects including winterisation assistance such as shelter kits for people living in collective shelters and unfinished buildings. In addition we have supplied 1,545 winterised tents and 4,720 thermal blankets for various UN agencies and NGO partners to distribute across affected areas including to families vulnerable in the winter climate. Our Advisors on the ground are working closely with aid agencies, the UN and the Kurdistan Regional Government to ensure that there is both an accurate assessment of need and an effective plan for meeting it. The UK will continue to closely monitor the situation in the Kurdish and wider regions of Iraq.</p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Northover",,"2014-10-21T16:35:30.5506625Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93410/answer","Biography information for Baroness Northover","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93410/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93410/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2014-10-14","Middle East","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have considered relocating tented facilities from Afghanistan to the Kurdish regional area to house displaced refugees; and what discussions they have had with the Kurdish authorities about providing adequate shelter for refugees during the winter months.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL2076"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93411","Home Office","false","2014-10-27","<p>The Government ensures that asylum seekers are not left destitute by providing accommodation and a cash allowance to cover their essential living needs.</p><p>The table below sets out the current weekly allowances provided to asylum seekers and various categories of dependants that may also be supported.</p><table><tbody><tr><td> </td><td><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="2"><p><strong>LEVELS OF CASH SUPPORT FROM 18 APRIL 2011</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>£</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td>SINGLE PERSON</td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Aged 18 or over (excluding lone parent)</p></td><td><p>36.62</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Aged 25 years or over (excluding lone parent), where the decision to provide cash support was made before 5 October 2009 and the person reached age 25 prior to that date.</p></td><td><p>42.62</p></td></tr><tr><td>QUALIFYING COUPLES</td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Both 18 years or over</p></td><td><p>72.52</p></td></tr><tr><td>LONE PARENT AGE 18 OR OVER</td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Age 18 or over</p></td><td><p>43.94</p></td></tr><tr><td>PERSONAL ALLOWANCE FOR DEPENDENT CHILDREN</td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Person aged under 16</p></td><td><p>52.96</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Person aged 16 but under 18 (except where the person is a member of a Qualifying Couple)</p></td><td><p>39.80</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p></td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr><tr><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td><td> </td></tr></tbody></table><p>The Government has reviewed the allowances and concluded that the allowances are sufficient to cover the essential needs of asylum seekers and their families.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2014-10-27T15:47:49.7271209Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93411/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93411/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93411/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-10-14","Asylum: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is the current rate of support provided to asylum seekers; and how many of those who receive such support they estimate to live below the poverty line.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL2077"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93412","Home Office","false","2014-10-27","<p>The information requested in the noble Lord's question could only be obtained through a manual search of individual case files, which would incur adisproportionate cost. However, we do publish information on the outcome of asylum applications which may assist the noble Lord. This can be found at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/345774/asylum2-q2-2014-tabs.ods" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/345774/asylum2-q2-2014-tabs.ods</a></p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2014-10-27T12:39:56.8485295Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93412/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93412/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93412/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-10-14","Asylum","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many asylum seekers have had their application refused but could not be returned to their country of origin in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL2078"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93413","Home Office","false","2014-10-27","<p>The Home Office operates two Assisted Voluntary Return (AVR) schemes for those without permanent immigration status in the UK and for which failed asylum seekers are eligible. These are:</p><p> </p><p>Voluntary Assisted Return and Reintegration Programme (VARRP) for those who have sought asylum and those with discretionary leave in the UK. Returnees receive support in acquiring travel documentation, flight to the country of return and onward domestic transport, airport assistance at departure and arrival airports and up to £1500 worth of reintegration assistance per person.</p><p> </p><p>Assisted Voluntary Return for Families and Children (AVRFC) is for families comprising of a maximum of 2 adult parents or legal guardians and at least 1 child (under 18), and also unaccompanied children (under 18) who have either sought asylum or who are in the UK illegally and wish to return home. Returnees receive support in acquiring travel documentation, flight to the country of return and onward domestic transport, airport assistance at departure and arrival airports and up to £2000 worth of reintegration assistance per person.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2014-10-27T12:38:19.2587947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93413/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93413/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93413/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2014-10-14","Asylum","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assistance is offered to failed asylum seekers in order to help them return to their country of origin.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL2079"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93414","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-10-27","<p>Refugees recognised by the UK Government, along with their husband, wife, civil partner and children, are eligible for funding to attend an English for Speakers of Other Languages course. The level of funding is determined by existing eligibility rules, which are set out in the Skills Funding Agency’s rules at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/287917/Funding_rules_2014_15.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/287917/Funding_rules_2014_15.pdf</a>. Education and skills funding is devolved and the eligibility criteria apply to England.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Those isolated by their lack of English can also access pre-entry level English training through the Department for Communities and Local Government’s £6million Community-Based English Language programme, which offers tuition to 24,000 adults most isolated by their lack of English in 29 target areas.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2014-10-27T16:44:21.3307113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93414/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93414/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93414/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-10-14","Asylum: English Language","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assistance is given to successful asylum seekers who wish to learn English.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL2080"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93415","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-10-22","<p>The most recent figures we have are taken from a 2010 report prepared by the Institute of Public Policy Research which was commissioned by the Foreign and Commonwealth Office’s Consular Directorate. These figures are estimates of the number of UK citizens living abroad (including for part of a year).</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>EU Member State</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>UK Citizens living in Member State (estimate - including for part of the year)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Austria</p></td><td><p>7,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Belgium</p></td><td><p>31,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Bulgaria</p></td><td><p>18,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Croatia</p></td><td><p>Not a Member State at the time the report was commissioned</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Cyprus</p></td><td><p>65,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Czech Republic</p></td><td><p>7,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Denmark</p></td><td><p>12,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Estonia</p></td><td><p>700</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Finland</p></td><td><p>4,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>France</p></td><td><p>330,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Germany</p></td><td><p>107,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Greece</p></td><td><p>45,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Hungary</p></td><td><p>5,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Ireland</p></td><td><p>329,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Italy</p></td><td><p>37,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Latvia</p></td><td><p>400</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Lithuania</p></td><td><p>300</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Luxembourg</p></td><td><p>8,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Malta</p></td><td><p>11,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Netherlands</p></td><td><p>48,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Poland</p></td><td><p>6,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Portugal</p></td><td><p>39,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Romania</p></td><td><p>7,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Slovakia</p></td><td><p>1,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Slovenia</p></td><td><p>4,000</p></td></tr><tr>