"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93059","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2014-10-20","<p>We are concerned about all instances of anti-Semitism, and regularly raise this issue with a number of countries, including those referred to in the Honorable Member's question, though we do not hold a central record of every time we have done so. Our Embassies and High Commissions monitor cases of anti-Semitism and raise them with their host governments. We support the efforts of EU partners to tackle racism in all its forms. For instance, a number of Ministers, including the Home Secretary, strongly condemned the murders at the Jewish Museum in Brussels in May.</p><p>Anti-Semitism (and particularly Holocaust denial and denigration) are regularly discussed during meetings of the International Holocaust Remembrance Alliance (IHRA) in a dedicated Committee, and as a formal agenda item during the plenary meetings held twice a year. The UK Envoy for Post-Holocaust Issues, Sir Andrew Burns, leads an active UK delegation in these discussions. All the states to which your question refers are members of IHRA, with the exception of Australia.</p><p>The Foreign and Commonwealth Office also works very closely with the UK Member of the European Commission against Racism and Intolerance (ECRI), who provides expert advice on tackling anti-Semitism to the British Government and internationally.</p><p>The British Government will be represented at a senior level at the tenth anniversary of the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) Conference and Declaration on Anti-Semitism, being held in Berlin on 13 November 2014.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2014-10-20T14:59:13.4979833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93059/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93059/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93059/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2014-10-13","Antisemitism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many times he or Ministers in his Department have raised concerns about anti-Semitism with their counterparts in (a) France, (b) Germany, (c) Holland, (d) Belgium, (e) Poland, (f) Australia, (g) the US and (h) Ireland since 2010.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","210224"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93060","Department for Transport","false","2014-10-16","<p>In the latter half of Control Period 4 (2009-14) it became clear that Network Rail faced serious Executive retention risks which threatened leadership continuity. Accordingly, at the company’s 2012 Annual General Meeting, Network Rail’s members agreed one-off performance related retention payments for three Executive Directors if they remained in post for the entirety of the Control Period. These retention payments were implemented when Network Rail was a private sector company limited by guarantee.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>On 1 September Network Rail was reclassified to the public sector. As an arm’s-length public sector body, it must use public money proportionately and with probity and ensure that reward and remuneration do not go beyond what is needed to ensure sustained high performance. As part of new governance arrangements, Executive Director remuneration will be set by Network Rail’s Remuneration Committee but must be approved by the Secretary of State and the Chief Secretary to HM Treasury. Under the company’s remuneration policy for Control Period 5 (2014-19), no further retention payments can be awarded to serving Directors.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2014-10-16T14:15:11.6305188Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93060/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93060/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93060/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-10-13","Network Rail","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, for what reasons retention bonuses have been paid to Network Rail executives; and what his policy is on the further payment of such bonuses.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","210268"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93061","HM Treasury","false","2014-10-16","<p>Tax reliefs are administrated as part of the tax system and are subject to different rules to public expenditure.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>HM Treasury and Her Majesty’s Revenue and Customs (HMRC) keep all aspects of the tax system under review to ensure the effectiveness of tax reliefs and to prevent abuse. HMRC has responsibility for administering and monitoring tax reliefs for abuse and, with HM Treasury, is responsible for appraising and evaluating any aspects of the tax system.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The introduction of all tax reliefs or changes to their design and scope are subject to Parliamentary spending scrutiny during the Finance Bill process.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","210154 ; 210157 ; 210158","2014-10-16T16:59:27.7478303Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93061/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93061/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93061/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-10-13","Business: Government Assistance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will make an assessment of the effectiveness of government financial support to business through grants and tax foregone.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","210155"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93062","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-11-10","<p>The Department’s finance systems do not hold data on total government support to business since 2010.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2014-11-10T15:43:02.0895613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93062/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93062/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93062/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-10-13","Business: Government Assistance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how much the Government has spent in grants and support schemes to businesses since 2010.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","210156"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93063","HM Treasury","false","2014-10-16","<p>Tax reliefs are administrated as part of the tax system and are subject to different rules to public expenditure.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>HM Treasury and Her Majesty’s Revenue and Customs (HMRC) keep all aspects of the tax system under review to ensure the effectiveness of tax reliefs and to prevent abuse. HMRC has responsibility for administering and monitoring tax reliefs for abuse and, with HM Treasury, is responsible for appraising and evaluating any aspects of the tax system.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The introduction of all tax reliefs or changes to their design and scope are subject to Parliamentary spending scrutiny during the Finance Bill process.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","210154 ; 210155 ; 210158","2014-10-16T16:59:27.8416277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93063/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93063/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93063/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-10-13","Tax Allowances: Business","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the cost to the Exchequer of tax relief to businesses since 2010.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","210157"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93064","HM Treasury","false","2014-10-16","<p>Tax reliefs are administrated as part of the tax system and are subject to different rules to public expenditure.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>HM Treasury and Her Majesty’s Revenue and Customs (HMRC) keep all aspects of the tax system under review to ensure the effectiveness of tax reliefs and to prevent abuse. HMRC has responsibility for administering and monitoring tax reliefs for abuse and, with HM Treasury, is responsible for appraising and evaluating any aspects of the tax system.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The introduction of all tax reliefs or changes to their design and scope are subject to Parliamentary spending scrutiny during the Finance Bill process.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","210154 ; 210155 ; 210157","2014-10-16T16:59:27.5135075Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93064/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93064/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93064/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-10-13","Business: Government Assistance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how often he reviews the cost effectiveness of corporate welfare schemes; and what the criteria are for such schemes to be continued.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","210158"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93065","HM Treasury","false","2014-10-16","<p>Tax reliefs are administrated as part of the tax system and are subject to different rules to public expenditure.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>HM Treasury and Her Majesty’s Revenue and Customs (HMRC) keep all aspects of the tax system under review to ensure the effectiveness of tax reliefs and to prevent abuse. HMRC has responsibility for administering and monitoring tax reliefs for abuse and, with HM Treasury, is responsible for appraising and evaluating any aspects of the tax system.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The introduction of all tax reliefs or changes to their design and scope are subject to Parliamentary spending scrutiny during the Finance Bill process.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","210155 ; 210157 ; 210158","2014-10-16T16:59:27.6384581Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93065/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93065/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93065/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2014-10-13","Business: Government Assistance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the total funds provided by Government for (a) corporate welfare grants and support schemes and (b) tax forgone.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","210154"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93361","Department for Transport","false","2014-10-16","<p>Local authorities have a statutory duty to determine whether someone is fit and proper to hold a driver’s licence and as part of this process they can request an enhanced criminal records check.</p><p> </p><p>After careful consideration, the Government has decided not to pursue clause 10 of the Deregulation Bill which would have allowed leisure use of private hire vehicles. We consider this measure is now better considered as part of the proposals in the Law Commission’s review of taxi and private hire vehicle licensing.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2014-10-16T10:14:50.8136101Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93361/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93361/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93361/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-10-13","Taxis: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment he has made of the effects of the Government's reforms of taxi and minicab licensing on the safety of women passengers.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","905449"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93487","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-10-16","<p>The Arts Council’s announcements on their 2015-2018 portfolio continue a trend in the reduction of the share of funding that is going to organisations in London, and includes investment in retaining talent and boosting production capacity outside of London. This includes the East Midlands which I will be visiting later this month.</p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2014-10-16T16:18:51.1467889Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93487/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93487/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93487/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-10-13","Arts: East Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what representations he has received on funding for culture in the East Midlands.","false","Biography information for Sir Edward Leigh","Gainsborough","Sir Edward Leigh","905470"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93488","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-10-16","<p>The government supported amendments in the Deregulation Bill and has committed to a thorough, independent review of how the licence fee is enforced. The Secretary of State announced last month that the Review will begin shortly and will conclude early in the next parliament.</p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2014-10-16T11:59:25.4703457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93488/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93488/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93488/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-10-13","Television: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps he is taking to review the rules relating to non-payment of the TV licence fee.","false","Biography information for Karl McCartney","Lincoln","Karl McCartney","905458"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93660","Women and Equalities","false","2014-10-16","<p>I regularly discuss with ministerial colleagues the Government’s commitment to the protection and advancement of women’s rights both domestically and overseas. In the summer we hosted two global events – a summit with a focus on preventing sexual violence in conflict which generated strong international support; and a girl summit. The Girl Summit brought together a range of international stakeholders to accelerate momentum in tackling child, early and forced marriage and female genital mutilation and to rally a global movement to end the practices everywhere within a generation.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>We are also strong supporters of a stand-alone goal on gender equality and women’s empowerment in the post-2015 development framework.</p><p> </p>","East Dunbartonshire","Jo Swinson",,"2014-10-16T15:44:24.2876047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93660/answer","Biography information for Jo Swinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93660/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93660/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2014-10-13","Human Rights: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Ministers for Women and Equalities, what recent discussions she has had with her ministerial colleagues on protecting the rights of women and girls overseas.","false","Biography information for Stephen Mosley","City of Chester","Stephen Mosley","905451"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93717","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-10-16","<p>DCMS is investing up to £8 million each year in 13/14 and 14/15 through the Skills Investment Fund. With industry match funding, this will support skills development in the film, TV, and video games sectors. By March 2015, Creative Skillset estimate that in total, over £4,300,000 of SIF funding will have been spent on training for the games sector. One element of this Fund, the Trainee Finder scheme, has so far placed 122 trainees in 67 games companies.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2014-10-16T16:17:06.8628096Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93717/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93717/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93717/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-10-13","Video Games","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what amount the Government has allocated to the Creative Skillset Skills Investment Fund; how much of that funding has been allocated to the video games industry; and what assessment he has made of the effects of that funding.","false","Biography information for Jim McGovern","Dundee West","Jim McGovern","905475"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93718","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2014-10-16","<p>Funding decisions for the arts are made independently of Ministers by Arts Council England. Earlier this year the Arts Council announced an increase in the proportion of spend on regional arts and major partner museums and the Government is committed to achieving a better balance from public funding and Lottery investment across the country.</p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2014-10-16T16:17:53.0960157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93718/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93718/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/93718/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2014-10-13","Arts: Government Assistance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps his department is taking to support theatre and the arts in the provinces.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","905477"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92431","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-10-17","<p>The national Community Learning (CL) objectives focus strongly on tackling disadvantage, including digital exclusion. Data for 2012/13 show that 9.4 per cent of all CL enrolments were in ICT subjects, with 97,310 learners participating.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Department for Business, Innovation and Skills (BIS) separately funds the Tinder Foundation to deliver a wide range of digital inclusion projects. Many BIS-funded learning providers - mainly Local Authority adult education services - work closely with the Tinder Foundation and UK online centres on a range of digital inclusion projects.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In addition BIS has run a series of basic digital skills training programmes with Tinder in recent years. These have helped 1.25m people gain the skills they need to become confident and safe internet users.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2014-10-17T13:34:16.0269808Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92431/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92431/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92431/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-10-10","Adult and Community Learning Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what proportion of the Community Learning Fund supports digital inclusion projects or projects that equip learners with digital skills.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","209839"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92432","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2014-10-17","<p>BIS contributes £210m pa to support community learning (CL) via the Community Learning budget, which is managed by the Skills Funding Agency. Funding is allocated via a grant arrangement with 315 learning providers, including Local Authority adult education services, Further Education colleges, and voluntary sector organisations. Many learning providers work with local sub-contractors.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The CL budget helps to support an on-going adult education offer in every area, rather than short term projects. Community Learning courses:</p><p> </p><p>· meet a variety of learning needs, from personal development to pre-employment skills, health and wellbeing, parenting skills, crafts and languages</p><p> </p><p>· are free - or nearly free - for people who are disadvantaged, with more affluent learners paying according to their means</p><p> </p><p>· use flexible teaching and learning approaches and take place in accessible local venues in order to engage a wide range of people, including those who are very disadvantaged</p><p> </p><p>· have varied outcomes, including improved confidence, better mental/physical health, confident parenting and progression to formal training and/or employment.</p><p> </p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2014-10-17T13:23:50.2441935Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92432/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92432/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/92432/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2014-10-10","Adult and Community Learning Fund","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how the Community Learning Fund is distributed; and what projects that Fund currently supports.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","209840"
